19","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotsko, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland"},"da":{"1250–":"1250–Afdød","1248–Male":"1248–Afdød","1270–1319":"1270–1319","1250–Female":"1250–Afdød","1248":"1248","about 1269":"omkring 1269","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1319":"1319","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Skotland","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"1250–":"1250–Overleden","1248–Male":"1248–Overleden","1270–1319":"1270–1319","1250–Female":"1250–Overleden","1248":"1248","about 1269":"circa 1269","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1319":"1319","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1250–":"1250–Deceased","1248–Male":"1248–Deceased","1270–1319":"1270–1319","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","1248":"1248","about 1269":"about 1269","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1319":"1319","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacDonald","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McDonald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McDonald","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Domhnaill</i> ‘son of <i>Domhnall</i>’, a name derived from the Celtic elements <i>domno-</i> ‘world’ + <i>val-</i> ‘might, rule’. <i>Donald</i> is an Anglicized form (via Latin) of this personal name used in Scotland, though the surname is also widespread in Ireland. The name is equivalent to Irish   McDonnell   and   McConnell  , and to Manx   Cannell  .","History: This is the name of the largest and most disparate of the Scottish clans (Clan Donald), associated in particular with the Hebrides and claiming descent from Domhnall mac Raghnaill mac Somhairle, who lived in the late 12th century. From that time until 1493 the head of the clan was known as Lord (or King) of the Isles. The reigns of the Lords of the Isles were always stormy, often in conflict with the kings of Scotland, and peppered with disasters. After a series of defeats in the 1480s, Eoin Mac Dhomhnaill a Ìle (John Macdonald of Islay, Earl of Ross and Lord of the Isles) forfeited his lands, his power, and his title as Lord of the Isles in 1493 to King James IV of Scotland. By then, a branch of the family had settled in the Antrim Glens in Ireland and members moved between the southern Hebrides and Ireland throughout the 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret MacDonald was born in 1250, in Scotland. She married Alexander FitzJames about 1269, in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1250–":"1250–Surnud","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1270–1319":"1270–1319","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1248":"1248","about 1269":"umbes 1269","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1319":"1319","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1250–":"1250–Kuollut","1248–Male":"1248–Kuollut","1270–1319":"1270–1319","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1248":"1248","about 1269":"noin 1269","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1319":"1319","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Scotland","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1250–":"1250–Décédée","1248–Male":"1248–Décédé","1270–1319":"1270–1319","1250–Female":"1250–Décédée","1248":"1248","about 1269":"environ 1269","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1319":"1319","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Scotlan